default3.7
default              
defaultChildren should have the right to their own legal counsel and representation, in their own name, in proceedings where 
defaultthere is, or could be, a conflict of interest between the child and the parents or other involved parties.
default3.8  
defaultChildren should have access to free legal aid, under the same or more lenient conditions as adults.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe residence testdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThis goes against Article 16 of the Refugee Convention 1951, which provides that ‘[a] refugee shall have free access to the courts of law on the terr
defaultitory of all Contracting States’ and that ‘[a]
default 
defaultrefugee shall enjoy in the Contracting State in which he has his habitual residence the same treatment as a national in matters pertaining to access to the Courts, including legal assistance and exemption from
default cautio judicatum solvi.’
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThis leaves many other types of case that relate to safeguarding childre
defaultn subject to the residence test. This includes
default for example age dispute judicial reviews 
defaultthat determine whether someone is a child (the safeguarding consequences of which 
defaultare extremely serious including a child potentially being detained in an adult prison or immigration removal centre or housed in unsupervised accommodation with adults). This also includes 
defaultany other judicial review of the practice of local authorities or o
defaultther public bodies in 
defaultrelation to their duties to protect
default children. 
defaultThe 
defaultproposed residence
default test noticeably 
defaultstill applies to
default cases concerning section 17 of the Children Act 1989 - duties to children in need.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe exempti
defaulton thus 
defaultleaves very significant gaps in the civil legal aid that trafficking 
defaultvictims can access. They will not have access to civil legal aid in public law, leaving them unable to bring a judicial review. This is striking because the only way to challenge 
defaulta negative reasonable or conclusive grounds decision is by judicial review. They will not be able to access legal aid in community care, for example if a child or young person is unlawfully denied services by a local authority or unlawfully age disputed.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe immigration applications contained in the exemption are very narrow: it is only where a
default victim of domestic violence can make specific applications that they access civil legal for this. In our experience, many victims of domestic violence would not fall into these exemptions in relation to their immigration applications.
default&#xa0;
defaultMoreover, the resid
defaultence test remains in relation to significant areas of civil law relevant to victims of domestic violence and forced marriage, including public law, community care, civil actions and actions against the police. For example, if an undocumented migrant mother
default was the victim of domestic violence, had to leave the home and was facing destitution with her children, and the 
defaultlocal authorit
defaulty
default failed to meet its duties to the children, she would not get legal aid for a community care or public law lawyer to challenge 
defaultthis.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThis means tha
defaultt applications for bail made by those held in immigration detention are covered. However, immigration detainees will not be able to access civil legal aid in many important areas. This includes civil actions for damages for unlawful detention
default, or civil cla
defaultims arising from mistreatment in detention or discrimination
default. Very significantly, age-disputed children held in immigration detention as adults will not be able to access community care or public law legal aid to challenge an unlawful age assessment by a l
defaultocal authority.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThis leaves an enormo
defaultus array of judicial reviews 
defaultsubject to the residence test. To take some examples from CCLC’s practice, we will not be able to challenge unlawful age assessments where a child does not pass the residence test; we will not be able to challenge unlawful failures by local authorities to 
defaultmeet duties to 
defaultchildren where children do
default not pass the residence test; and we will not be able to bring judicial reviews to challenge the manifest failings of the Home Office in relation to children and young people where they do not meet the residence tes
defaultt. Whole developing areas of law around 
defaultthe rights of 
defaultthose who do not have leave in the UK
default, some of the most vulnerable people in this country, are likely to
default disappear. We believe limiting access to the courts in this way has extremely significant constit
defaultutional implications, thr
defaulteatens the rule of law, and undermines
default the government’s obligation
defaults to protect
default human rights, and particularly
default children’s rights.
